<h2>What Is Seasonal Affective Disorder?</h2>
<p>Seasonal Affective Disorder (SAD) is a subtype of major depressive disorder that follows a seasonal pattern — most commonly a fall/winter onset with spring remission. A less common summer-onset pattern also exists. SAD is not "the winter blues" — it is clinical depression with a seasonal trigger, involving the full symptom picture of major depression and significant impairment.</p>

<p>SAD affects approximately 1–6% of the population depending on latitude, with rates significantly higher in northern latitudes with shorter winter daylight. A further 10–15% of people experience subsyndromal SAD (sometimes called "winter blues") — subclinical seasonal mood changes that don't meet full diagnostic criteria but still meaningfully affect wellbeing.</p>

<h2>What Causes SAD</h2>
<p>The biological mechanisms of SAD are better understood than most depression subtypes:</p>

<p><strong>Circadian disruption:</strong> Reduced winter light delays the circadian phase — the body's internal clock shifts, producing mismatch between biological rhythms and environmental/social demands. This phase delay is central to SAD.</p>

<p><strong>Serotonin dysregulation:</strong> People with SAD show reduced serotonin transporter activity and lower serotonin levels in winter months, explaining the utility of SSRIs.</p>

<p><strong>Melatonin:</strong> Longer nights produce extended melatonin secretion. Some research suggests people with SAD may be hypersensitive to this change.</p>

<h2>Evidence-Based Treatments</h2>

<h3>Light Therapy</h3>
<p>Light therapy — daily exposure to 10,000 lux bright light for 20–30 minutes each morning — is the best-studied and most effective treatment for SAD. It directly addresses the circadian delay mechanism. Response rates are 50–80% and effects are rapid, often within 1–2 weeks. Light therapy devices are widely available and inexpensive relative to other treatments. Timing matters: morning light therapy is significantly more effective than evening.</p>

<h3>CBT for SAD</h3>
<p>CBT specifically adapted for SAD (CBT-SAD) targets the behavioural withdrawal and negative thought patterns specific to winter depression. Importantly, CBT-SAD shows better long-term outcomes than light therapy — preventing future episodes rather than just treating the current one. A combination is more effective than either alone.</p>

<h3>Medication</h3>
<p>SSRIs (fluoxetine, sertraline) are effective for SAD and are often combined with light therapy for more severe presentations. Bupropion XL has specific FDA approval for SAD prevention — started in early autumn before symptoms typically begin.</p>

<h2>Lifestyle Factors That Matter</h2>
<p>Exercise has evidence for improving SAD symptoms. Getting outside during daylight hours, even on overcast days (outdoor light is significantly brighter than indoor lighting), helps. Maintaining social engagement during winter — which becomes difficult as symptoms progress — is also protective.</p>

<h2>Online Therapy for SAD</h2>
<p>CBT-SAD is highly compatible with online delivery. Sessions can be scheduled during daylight hours, and therapists can guide light therapy usage and behavioural activation alongside cognitive work. Online access is particularly valuable for people in rural or high-latitude areas where both daylight and in-person mental health services may be limited.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<p><strong>Is SAD just about vitamin D?</strong><br/>
Vitamin D deficiency is more common in winter and correlates with depression, but the evidence for vitamin D supplementation treating SAD specifically is weak. Light therapy, which works through circadian mechanisms rather than vitamin D, is the primary biological intervention.</p>

<p><strong>Should I start light therapy or therapy first?</strong><br/>
Starting both at the same time is ideal. Light therapy produces faster initial symptom reduction; CBT-SAD produces more durable outcomes. If you can only choose one to start, light therapy is easier to begin immediately while seeking a therapist.</p>

<p><strong>Can SAD be prevented?</strong><br/>
Yes. CBT-SAD in autumn (before symptoms onset) reduces episode occurrence. Bupropion XL started prophylactically in autumn has FDA approval for SAD prevention. Maintaining light therapy and exercise through autumn is also protective.</p>

